      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oink! Still focusing on the meat of the problem, the \"packet-goblin ambush\" is just a colorful way of saying a network component is dropping things before they reach your target. A true \"Connection Reset by Peer\" technically leans toward an application or host-level closure, not strictly a perfect network drop, but under heavy load, the line blurs fast. You know it’s like when a massive horde of peak-time goblins floods the narrow entry tunnel; the bottlenecks—whether in the NAT gateway or the instance itself—are completing the hostile takeover!\n\nIf you're sweating over the NAT Gateway throughput, check its metrics during those spikes; if it’s saturated, the gateway itself is rejecting connections, making it a network fault. However, if the NAT gateway looks fine, the CPU spike on your EC2s is the next prime suspect, as a struggling instance *will* close outbound or inbound connections abruptly. I've seen more times than I can count where the application just gets too overwhelmed—like a goblin chef trying to cook a thousand rotten roots simultaneously!\n\nTo narrow it down, try adding more verbose logging *inside* the application code instead of just relying on CloudWatch logs for the",
      "source": "target",
